## Top 5 Things Already Done Well

These are genuine strengths. Don't change them.

---

### 1. ✅ Plan system architecture — best code in the entire project

[plans.js](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/lib/plans.js) + [usePlan.js](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/hooks/usePlan.js) is textbook feature-first permission design:
- Central feature-to-plan mapping — one line to add a feature
- Hierarchical levels — automatically handles "Creator includes everything Plus has"
- Clean hook binding — pages just ask `canSharePublicVault?` without knowing the rules
- Zero duplication — the logic exists in exactly one place

**This should be the reference pattern for everything else you build.**

---

### 2. ✅ Choosing Supabase as the backend

Supabase gives you authentication, database, storage, and real-time capabilities without building a server. For a solo developer building a SaaS, this was the right call. It handles:
- OAuth + email/password auth
- SQL parameterization (preventing injection)
- HTTPS enforcement
- Session management
- File storage with CDN

You got 80% of a backend for free. The remaining 20% (RLS, Edge Functions) just needs to be configured.

---

### 3. ✅ Service layer pattern

The decision to create `authService.js` and `promptService.js` as intermediaries between your UI and Supabase was correct. Even though it's bypassed in some places (which needs fixing), the pattern itself is sound:
- Pages don't need to know the database schema
- Swapping Supabase for another backend means changing only the service files
- Error handling can be centralized

---

### 4. ✅ Defensive UI rendering

Your JSX is consistently well-guarded against null/undefined data:
- `profile?.full_name || username` — fallbacks everywhere
- `p.name || ''` before `.toLowerCase()` — prevents null crashes
- Conditional rendering for social links, avatars, plan badges
- Loading states before data arrives

Across 28 failure scenarios tested, your UI rendering never crashes on missing data.

---

### 5. ✅ Design system consistency

Outside of Auth/CompleteProfile (which use their own CSS), your Tailwind-based design system is consistent:
- CSS variables for colors (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`)
- Consistent typography (`font-mono` for UI labels, `font-inter` for body text)
- Uniform spacing and interaction patterns
- The monospaced, uppercase, developer-tool aesthetic is distinctive and carried throughout

